<ns7571:section xmlns:ns7571="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.technologies.java.tools.xml.xom.disadvantages">
    <ns7572:title xmlns:ns7572="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">The Disadvantages of XOM</ns7572:title>
   
    <ns7573:section xmlns:ns7573="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        <ns7574:title xmlns:ns7574="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Not a standard part of Java SE</ns7574:title>
        <ns7575:para xmlns:ns7575="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
            Usage of XOM means that the XOM library must be bundled with your application. In addition,
            this may pose a problem to applications deployed on non-standard devices, such as Cellular
            phones or microwave ovens.
        </ns7575:para>
    </ns7573:section>
    
    <ns7576:section xmlns:ns7576="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        <ns7577:title xmlns:ns7577="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Does not take advantage of Java SE 5 features</ns7577:title>
        <ns7578:para xmlns:ns7578="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
            Though this is true of <ns7579:emphasis xmlns:ns7579="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">all</ns7579:emphasis> current XML parsing APIs. However, because XOM is non-standard
            in anyway, code bulk (that makes use of XOM) could be even further reduced by making use of
            Java 5 features such as the <ns7580:literal xmlns:ns7580="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Iterable</ns7580:literal> interface (which would enable query results to
            be processed with the new <ns7581:literal xmlns:ns7581="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">for-loop</ns7581:literal>), or <ns7582:emphasis xmlns:ns7582="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">generics</ns7582:emphasis>, which could
            reduce casting.
        </ns7578:para>
        <ns7583:para xmlns:ns7583="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
            This may, however, be the case to still support older platforms with Java 1.4 deployed.
        </ns7583:para>
    </ns7576:section>
    
</ns7571:section>